+# GitHub release readiness
+
+## Bootstrap complete when
+
+- [ ] canonical source is present on `main`
+- [ ] commit and tree contents match the local verified release
+- [ ] CI completes successfully
+- [ ] Pages workflow either deploys successfully or records the required repository-setting change
+- [ ] `CODEOWNERS`, issue forms, pull-request template, Dependabot, and security policy are present
+- [ ] reference-repository reconnaissance is accurately documented
+- [ ] obsolete statements claiming connector unavailability have been removed
+- [ ] roadmap issues exist for migration audit, production foundation, public authority migration, and enterprise pilot
+
+## Repository-owner settings
+
+Settings not represented as files must be verified in GitHub:
+
+- branch/ruleset protection for `main`
+- required `CI / Verify` status check
+- private vulnerability reporting
+- Pages source set to GitHub Actions during prototype review
+- repository converted to private before non-public data or work product is introduced
+- secret scanning and push protection where available
+
+## Evidence to retain
+
+- initialization commit SHA
+- workflow run IDs and conclusions
+- Pages deployment URL and commit
+- open issue numbers for remaining gated work
+- final repository visibility and ruleset state
diff --git a/product/GOVERNANCE.md b/product/GOVERNANCE.md
new file mode 100644
index 0000000..9a60897
--- /dev/null
+++ b/product/GOVERNANCE.md
@@ -0,0 +1,144 @@
+# Legal intelligence and model governance
+
+## Governance objective
+
+The platform’s credibility depends less on a “verified” badge than on a reviewable operating system for sources, rules, calculations, analysis, and downstream artifacts.
+
+## Source lifecycle
+
+1. **Identify** — monitor authoritative publishers and known volatility points.
+2. **Acquire** — preserve the retrieved version, URI, timestamp, and content hash.
+3. **Classify** — identify authority type, jurisdiction, status, and effective dates.
+4. **Extract** — create passage-level propositions and candidate rule changes.
+5. **Review** — attorney/editor verifies text, dates, scope, and conflicts.
+6. **Publish** — release a versioned source and any affected rule versions.
+7. **Monitor** — watch for amendment, repeal, challenge, guidance, or access failure.
+8. **Supersede** — preserve history and trigger downstream revalidation.
+
+## Rule governance
+
+Every production rule version requires:
+
+- named legal owner
+- effective interval
+- supporting source passages
+- explicit coverage predicates
+- explicit exceptions
+- deterministic test fixtures where computable
+- review and approval history
+- disclosed interpretation points
+- rollback and supersession path
+
+Rules should not be edited in place after use. A material change creates a new version.
+
+## Calculation governance
+
+Every calculation module requires:
+
+- versioned specification
+- unit and integration tests
+- canonical fixtures
+- boundary-value tests
+- jurisdiction and date coverage matrix
+- explicit rounding rules
+- explainable branch trace
+- legal sign-off
+- release notes
+- production monitoring
+
+The user must be able to distinguish:
+
+- input fact
+- user assumption
+- derived value
+- rule branch
+- mathematical operation
+- legal judgment
+- limitation
+
+## Editorial governance
+
+Canonical analysis should include:
+
+- author and reviewer
+- last reviewed date
+- sources and passages
+- jurisdiction and effective scope
+- change log
+- unresolved issues
+- plain-language summary
+- deeper legal analysis
+- operational implications
+- educational-information disclaimer
+
+## Matter governance
+
+A matter should have:
+
+- owner
+- privilege and confidentiality designation
+- scope and lifecycle state
+- required reviewers
+- decision rights
+- due dates
+- evidence expectations
+- closure criteria
+- retention policy
+
+## Decision governance
+
+An approved decision record is immutable. Corrections or changes produce a new version. The record preserves:
+
+- exact content approved
+- supporting rule and source versions
+- fact snapshot
+- scenario/model version
+- named approvers and timestamps
+- conditions
+- known gaps
+- revalidation triggers
+
+## Assurance governance
+
+A control cannot be labeled “effective” solely because a policy exists. Status should reflect:
+
+- design completeness
+- implementation
+- operating cadence
+- evidence receipt
+- test result
+- exception severity
+- remediation
+- assurance acceptance
+
+Evidence should expire or require refresh according to cadence.
+
+## AI governance
+
+AI can assist with retrieval, summarization, proposition extraction, comparison, and drafting. It may not silently become the source of truth.
+
+Required controls:
+
+- retrieval restricted by permission and data class
+- source citations at passage level
+- no unsupported legal propositions
+- clear separation of generated text and approved analysis
+- prompt and model version logging for material outputs
+- human review gates
+- redaction and data-loss prevention
+- evaluation sets for citation accuracy, completeness, and abstention
+- incident response for erroneous or cross-tenant output
+
+## Operating roles
+
+| Role | Accountability |
+|---|---|
+| Legal content owner | substantive legal accuracy and scope |
+| Editorial reviewer | clarity, citation, consistency, publication standard |
+| Rule engineer | normalized predicates and deterministic implementation |
+| Model validator | calculation tests, fixtures, and release acceptance |
+| Data steward | enterprise fact quality and freshness |
+| Matter owner | scoped response and decision continuity |
+| Control owner | operation and evidence production |
+| Assurance owner | independent review and exception acceptance |
+| Product/security | permissions, auditability, resilience, and user experience |
diff --git a/product/IMPLEMENTATION-ROADMAP.md b/product/IMPLEMENTATION-ROADMAP.md
